    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-16T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-16T18:00:00-05:00" n="434"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. No. 763.72112Am1/51</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Honduras</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CCB1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-16T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 16, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your February 9, 6 p.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d434fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    Department’s February 6, 7 p.m. Department stated resumption of traffic through
                    agency of Pacific Mail at Amapala was approved.</p>
                <p>Since the contemplated operation of German-owned lighters was only until “agency
                    was established and had secured other lighters” (January 18, 1 p.m. [<hi
                        rend="italic">midnight</hi>]),<note n="2" xml:id="d434fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_378">p. 378</ref>.</note> and
                    since this condition has been complied with, the necessity of possibly utilizing
                    German material no longer exists.</p>
                <p>In view of the early resumption of traffic at Amapala, Department feels confident
                    any past inconvenience has been eliminated.</p>
                <p>Legation’s January 24, 10 a.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d434fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    and January 23, 11 a.m. [<hi rend="italic">p.m.</hi>]<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d434fn4">Not printed.</note> do not indicate that in
                    government-seized lighters German taint has been eliminated. This phase of
                    question is at present before the War Trade Board.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
